#: ../../../prompt.rst:2
msgid "Writing your own prompt"
msgstr "編寫你自己的提示"

#: ../../../prompt.rst:7
msgid ""
"This document uses formatting to show what a prompt would look like. If you "
"are viewing this in the man page, you probably want to switch to looking at "
"the html version instead. Run ``help custom-prompt`` to view it in a web "
"browser."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:10
msgid ""
"Fish ships a number of prompts that you can view with the :doc:`fish_config "
"<cmds/fish_config>` command, and many users have shared their prompts online."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:12
msgid ""
"However, you can also write your own, or adjust an existing prompt. This is "
"a good way to get used to fish's :doc:`scripting language <language>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:14
msgid ""
"Unlike other shells, fish's prompt is built by running a function - :doc:"
"`fish_prompt <cmds/fish_prompt>`. Or, more specifically, three functions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:16
msgid ""
":doc:`fish_prompt <cmds/fish_prompt>`, which is the main prompt function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:17
msgid ""
":doc:`fish_right_prompt <cmds/fish_right_prompt>`, which is shown on the "
"right side of the terminal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:18
msgid ""
":doc:`fish_mode_prompt <cmds/fish_mode_prompt>`, which is shown if :ref:`vi "
"mode <vi-mode>` is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:20
msgid ""
"These functions are run, and whatever they print is displayed as the prompt "
"(minus one trailing newline)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:22
msgid ""
"If the :envvar:`SHELL_PROMPT_PREFIX` or :envvar:`SHELL_PROMPT_SUFFIX` "
"environment variables are set, they are automatically prepended and appended "
"to the left prompt."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:24
msgid "Here, we will just be writing a simple fish_prompt."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:27
msgid "Our first prompt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:29
msgid "Let's look at a very simple example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:31
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    echo $PWD '>'\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:35
msgid ""
"This prints the current working directory (:envvar:`PWD`) and a ``>`` symbol "
"to show where the prompt ends. The ``>`` is :ref:`quoted <quotes>` because "
"otherwise it would signify a :ref:`redirection <redirects>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:37
msgid ""
"Because we've used :doc:`echo <cmds/echo>`, it adds spaces between the two "
"so it ends up looking like (assuming ``_`` is your cursor):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:43
msgid ":white:`/home/tutorial >`\\ _"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:46
msgid "Formatting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:48
msgid ""
"``echo`` adds spaces between its arguments. If you don't want those, you can "
"use :doc:`string join <cmds/string-join>` like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:50
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    string join '' -- $PWD '>'\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:54
msgid ""
"The ``--`` indicates to ``string`` that no options can come after it, in "
"case we extend this with something that can start with a ``-``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:56
msgid ""
"There are other ways to remove the space, including ``echo -s`` and :doc:"
"`printf <cmds/printf>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:59
msgid "Adding color"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:61
msgid "This prompt is functional, but a bit boring. We could add some color."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:63
msgid ""
"Fortunately, fish offers the :doc:`set_color <cmds/set_color>` command, so "
"you can do::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:65
msgid "echo (set_color red)foo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:67
msgid ""
"``set_color`` can also handle RGB colors like ``set_color 23b455``, and "
"other formatting options including bold and italics."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:69
msgid "So, taking our previous prompt and adding some color::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:71
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    string join '' -- (set_color green) $PWD (set_color --reset) '>'\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:75
msgid ""
"\"--reset\" tells the terminal to go back to its default formatting options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:77
msgid ""
"``set_color`` works by producing an escape sequence, which is a special "
"piece of text that terminals interpret as instructions - for example, to "
"change color. So ``set_color red`` produces the same effect as::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:81
msgid "echo \\e\\[31m"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:83
msgid ""
"Although you can write your own escape sequences by hand, it's much easier "
"to use ``set_color``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:86
msgid "Shortening the working directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:88
msgid ""
"This is fine, but our :envvar:`PWD` can be a bit long, and we are typically "
"only interested in the last few directories. We can shorten this with the :"
"doc:`prompt_pwd <cmds/prompt_pwd>` helper that will give us a shortened "
"working directory::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:90
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    string join '' -- (set_color green) (prompt_pwd) (set_color --reset) "
"'>'\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:94
msgid ""
"``prompt_pwd`` takes options to control how much to shorten. For instance, "
"if we want to display the last two directories, we'd use ``prompt_pwd --full-"
"length-dirs 2``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:96
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    string join '' -- (set_color green) (prompt_pwd --full-length-dirs 2) "
"(set_color --reset) '>'\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:100
msgid ""
"With a current directory of \"/home/tutorial/Music/Lena Raine/Oneknowing\", "
"this would print"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:106
msgid ":green:`~/M/Lena Raine/Oneknowing`>_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:109
msgid "Status"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:111
msgid ""
"One important bit of information that every command returns is the :ref:"
"`status <variables-status>`. This is a whole number from 0 to 255, and "
"usually it is used as an error code - 0 if the command returned "
"successfully, or a number from 1 to 255 if not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:113
msgid ""
"It's useful to display this in your prompt, but showing it when it's 0 seems "
"kind of wasteful."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:115
msgid ""
"First of all, since every command (except for :doc:`set <cmds/set>`) changes "
"the status, you need to store it for later use as the first thing in your "
"prompt. Use a :ref:`local variable <variables-scope>` so it will be confined "
"to your prompt function::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:117
msgid "set -l last_status $status"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:119
msgid "And after that, you can set a string if it is not zero::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:121
msgid ""
"# Prompt status only if it's not 0\n"
"set -l stat\n"
"if test $last_status -ne 0\n"
"    set stat (set_color red)\"[$last_status]\"(set_color --reset)\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:127
msgid "And to print it, we add it to our ``string join``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:129
msgid ""
"string join '' -- (set_color green) (prompt_pwd) (set_color --reset) $stat "
"'>'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:131
msgid ""
"If ``$last_status`` was 0, ``$stat`` is empty, and so it will simply "
"disappear."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:133
msgid "So our entire prompt is now::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:135
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    set -l last_status $status\n"
"    # Prompt status only if it's not 0\n"
"    set -l stat\n"
"    if test $last_status -ne 0\n"
"        set stat (set_color red)\"[$last_status]\"(set_color --reset)\n"
"    end\n"
"\n"
"    string join '' -- (set_color green) (prompt_pwd) (set_color --reset) "
"$stat '>'\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:146
msgid "And it looks like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:153
msgid ""
":green:`~/M/L/Oneknowing`>false\n"
":green:`~/M/L/Oneknowing`\\ :red:`[1]`>_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:156
msgid "after we run ``false`` (which returns 1)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:161
msgid "Transient prompt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:163
msgid ""
"To enable transient prompt functionality, set the :envvar:"
"`fish_transient_prompt` variable to 1::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:165
msgid "set -g fish_transient_prompt 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:167
msgid ""
"With this set, fish re-runs prompt functions with a ``--final-rendering`` "
"argument before running a commandline. So you can use it to declutter your "
"old prompts. For example if you want to see only the current directory name "
"when you scroll up::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:170
msgid ""
"function fish_prompt\n"
"    set -l last_status $status\n"
"    set -l stat\n"
"    set -l pwd\n"
"    # Check if it's a transient or final prompt\n"
"    if contains -- --final-rendering $argv\n"
"        set pwd (path basename $PWD)\n"
"    else\n"
"        set pwd (prompt_pwd)\n"
"        # Prompt status only if it's not 0\n"
"        if test $last_status -ne 0\n"
"            set stat (set_color red)\"[$last_status]\"(set_color --reset)\n"
"        end\n"
"    end\n"
"\n"
"    string join '' -- (set_color green) $pwd (set_color --reset) $stat '>'\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:188
msgid ""
"Now running two commands in the same directory could result in this screen:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:195
msgid ""
":green:`Oneknowing`>false\n"
":green:`~/M/L/Oneknowing`\\ :red:`[1]`>_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:199
msgid "Save the prompt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:201
msgid ""
"Once you are happy with your prompt, you can save it with ``funcsave "
"fish_prompt`` (see :doc:`cmds/funcsave`) or write it to ~/.config/fish/"
"functions/fish_prompt.fish yourself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:203
msgid ""
"If you want to edit it again, open that file or use ``funced fish_prompt`` "
"(see :doc:`cmds/funced`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:206
msgid "Where to go from here?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:208
msgid ""
"We have now built a simple but working and usable prompt, but of course more "
"can be done."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:210
msgid "Fish offers more helper functions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:211
msgid ""
"``prompt_login`` to describe the user/hostname/container or "
"``prompt_hostname`` to describe just the host"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:212
msgid "``fish_is_root_user`` to help with changing the symbol for root."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:213
msgid ""
"``fish_vcs_prompt`` to show version control information (or "
"``fish_git_prompt`` / ``fish_hg_prompt`` / ``fish_svn_prompt`` to limit it "
"to specific systems)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../prompt.rst:214
msgid ""
"You can add a right prompt by changing :doc:`fish_right_prompt <cmds/"
"fish_right_prompt>` or a vi mode prompt by changing :doc:`fish_mode_prompt "
"<cmds/fish_mode_prompt>`."
msgstr ""

